What are Fullerenes and Why is Demand Increasing?
Fullerenes are a unique class of carbon allotropes composed entirely of carbon atoms arranged in hollow spherical, ellipsoidal, tubular, or cage-like molecular structures. The most well-known form, C60, commonly known as the "buckyball," consists of 60 carbon atoms arranged in a soccer ball-like configuration. Other variants include C70 and higher-order fullerene molecules, each offering distinctive electrical, thermal, mechanical, and chemical properties.

Unlike conventional carbon materials, fullerenes exhibit exceptional electron-accepting capability, outstanding thermal stability, remarkable mechanical strength, and superior antioxidant properties. These characteristics make them valuable across diverse industries, including semiconductor manufacturing, renewable energy, biomedical research, pharmaceuticals, cosmetics, advanced coatings, and nanocomposites. Continuous advances in nanotechnology, material science, and large-scale synthesis techniques are expanding commercial opportunities for fullerene-based products worldwide.

